caption.text:
Emm, ini memang jetlag, atau cuma sugesti, atau udah biasa ya? Hmm.

Anyway, akhirnya udah balik Indonesia lagi.

Perjalanan dari sejak awal banget berbulan2 lalu (audisi penyanyi? Lat konser 150 orang?) itu ultimately lead to 10 hari di negeri orang.

Banyak (banget!) hal-hal yang dikorbankan. Akademik, materi, tenaga, waktu, pikiran, dan berjubel printilan lain yang gabisa disebut semua.

Tapi semua ini sebanding.
Malahan sangat menguntungkan.
Dari hal2 konkret kayak kesempatan yang diperoleh, perkembangan vokal yang dirasakan, pengenalan budaya kita ke luar; sampe hal2 abstrak kayak tali kekeluargaan yang terjalin dengan makan bareng, cari dana bareng, latihan bareng, ngurusin ini itu bareng; itu semua sangat bernilai.

Nggak, nggak ada penyesalan ikut ICT. Menyesal malah, karena harusnya bisa konser lebih banyak, tapi belum diberi kesempatan.

Momen2 kemarin2 itulah, yang ndak akan pernah terlupakan.

ICT 2016 (belum) selesai.

‚ÄúConsider again that dot. That's home. That's us. On it everyone you love, everyone you know, everyone you ever heard of, every human being who ever was, lived out their lives. The aggregate of our joy and suffering, thousands of confident religions, ideologies, and economic doctrines, every hunter and forager, every hero and coward, every creator and destroyer of civilization, every king and peasant, every young couple in love, every mother and father, hopeful child, inventor and explorer, every teacher of morals, every corrupt politician, every "superstar," every "supreme leader," every saint and sinner in the history of our species lived there‚Äîon a mote of dust suspended in a sunbeam.

The Earth is a very small stage in a vast cosmic arena. Think of the endless cruelties visited by the inhabitants of one corner of this pixel on the scarcely distinguishable inhabitants of some other corner, how frequent their misunderstandings, how eager they are to kill one another, how fervent their hatreds. Think of the rivers of blood spilled by all those generals and emperors so that, in glory and triumph, they could become the momentary masters of a fraction of a dot.

Our posturings, our imagined self-importance, the delusion that we have some privileged position in the Universe, are challenged by this point of pale light. Our planet is a lonely speck in the great enveloping cosmic dark. In our obscurity, in all this vastness, there is no hint that help will come from elsewhere to save us from ourselves.

The Earth is the only world known so far to harbor life. There is nowhere else, at least in the near future, to which our species could migrate. Visit, yes. Settle, not yet. Like it or not, for the moment the Earth is where we make our stand.

It has been said that astronomy is a humbling and character-building experience. There is perhaps no better demonstration of the folly of human conceits than this distant image of our tiny world. To me, it underscores our responsibility to deal more kindly with one another, and to preserve and cherish the pale blue dot, the only home we've ever known.‚Äù
.
-Carl Sagan
